definition.value: LGBTQIA+ persons organized by occupation.
A person who writes poems.
A person who pilots aircraft.
A person who makes photographs.

Persons working in the provision of health services, whether as individual practitioners or employees of health institutions and programs, whether or not professionally trained, and whether or not subject to public regulation.

A person trained in pharmacy that prepares and dispenses drugs prescribed by physicians and health practitioners. The responsibilities include instructing patients on the use, hazards, interactions, and side effects of any drug dispensed.

Pharmacists with clinical training to provide patient-centered evidence-based pharmaceutical care. Clinical pharmacists assist with the design, implementation, monitoring, and modification of the patient's drug treatment.
A person belonging to a social class normally ranked immediately under royalty and found in some societies that have a formal aristocracy.
A rule of a barony; otherwise, a member of the lowest rank of English nobility (equivalent to a Scottish lord).

A hereditary title, below a peerage and senior to most knighthoods, entitling the bearer to the titular prefix "Sir" (for men) or "Dame" (for women) which is used in conjunction with the holder's Christian name. It is inheritable, usually by the eldest son, although a few baronetcies can also pass through the female line.
A noble person holding a rank intermediate between a duke and a baron.
The rule of a duchy or otherwise a high title of nobility, the holder of a dukedom.
A British or Irish nobleman next in rank above a viscount and below a marquess; equivalent to a European count. A female using the style is often termed a countess.
A title of nobility for a person ranking beneath a duke and above an earl.
A person who serves as a subject for artwork or fashion, usually in the medium of photography but also for painting or drawing.
One who studies linguistics.
One who studies or researches history.
Professionals who plan, organize and direct health education programs for the individual, groups and the community.
A person (or, rarely a thing) that is identified by members of a culture as representative of that culture.
A person who is an icon within the LGBTQIA+ community.
A person who is an icon within the gay male community.
A person who is an icon within the lesbian community.
A person who is an icon within the transgender community.
A person who is an icon within the bisexual community.
A person who belongs to or otherwise is a member of an organization.
A person who is a member of a secret society.
A member of the Free and Accepted Masons (sometimes entitled Ancient Free and Accepted Masons), an international fraternal and charitable organization.
A person in a narrative work of art (such as a novel, play, television series, or movie).
Persons in fictional works (film, television, books, etc.) who are LGBTQIA+.
A fictional person who is asexual.
A fictional person who is bisexual.
A fictional person who is pansexual.
A fictional person who is gay.
A fictional person who is transgender.
A fictional man who is gay.
A fictional woman who is lesbian.
A fictional man who is transgender.
A fictional woman who is transgender.
A fictional person who is nonbinary.
A person who makes designs for objects.
Someone who designs clothing professionally.

label.value: person who has committed a crime

definition.value: A person who is guilty of a crime, notably breaking the law.
One who writes computer programs.
Broadly, a cook; however, more commonly used to refer to the head cook of a restaurant or other establishment.

When used in reference to a cook with no sous-chefs or other workers beneath him, the term connotes a certain degree of prestige—whether culinary education or ability—distinguishing the chef from a “cook”. As a borrowing, chef was originally italicized, but such treatment is now obsolete. Within a catering establishment, the head cook (and no-one else) will normally be addressed simply as "chef" as a term of respect.
A person who has a high degree of recognition by the general population for his or her success or accomplishments; a famous person.
A celebrity who has acquired or developed their fame and notability through the Internet.

A person who has been castrated in any of various senses; that is, they've had some part of their internal or external reproductive organs removed or that those organs have otherwise been rendered unusable (such as via chemical castration).
A person who actively participates in physical sports, especially with great skill; a sportsperson.
People categorized by a particular philosophy or philosophies they endorsed, originated, or were otherwise strongly associated with.
One who believes in or advocates the absence of hierarchy and authority in most forms, especially one who works toward the realization of such.
A scholar or expert engaged in or contributing to philosophical inquiry.
